HEADWORD: Puck
<hw>Puck</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>pouke</ets>;
cf. OSw. <ets>puke</ets>, Icel. <ets>p⟦umac⟧ki</ets> an evil demon, W.
<ets>pwca</ets> a hobgoblin. Cf. <er>Poker</er> a bugbear,
<er>Pug</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Medi⟦ae⟧val Myth.)</fld> <def>A
celebrated fairy, ⟦ldquo⟧the merry wanderer of the night;⟦rdquo⟧ --
called also <altname>Robin Goodfellow</altname>, <altname>Friar
Rush</altname>, <altname>Pug</altname>, etc.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He meeteth <qex>Puck</qex>, whom most men call⟦br⟧
Hobgoblin, and on him doth fall.</q> <rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The goatsucker.</def>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Puck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Puck
<hw>Puck</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A disk of vulcanized
rubber used in the game of hockey, as the object to be driven through
the goals.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

